00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:20.360
The sun is one of hundreds
of billions

00:07:20.360 --> 00:07:22.700
of stars in the Milky Way galaxy.

00:07:22.700 --> 00:07:25.150
And some lucky nights
we're lucky to really look

00:07:25.150 --> 00:07:27.530
at a huge swath of stars.

00:07:27.530 --> 00:07:30.110
And for generations all we
could do is look at those stars

00:07:30.110 --> 00:07:33.360
and wonder, is the sun unique?

00:07:33.360 --> 00:07:36.550
Are we the only star out there
out of hundreds of billions

00:07:36.550 --> 00:07:37.850
that have planets around them?

00:07:37.850 --> 00:07:40.650
And that was the only
they we knew for sure.

00:07:40.650 --> 00:07:44.690
But scientists are persistent.

00:07:44.690 --> 00:07:48.180
Our technology develops
and allows us to learn more

00:07:48.180 --> 00:07:50.320
and more as time goes on.

00:07:50.320 --> 00:07:52.640
So one of the reasons we
didn't know about stars

00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:55.880
that had other planets was because
they're very, very hard to detect.

00:07:55.880 --> 00:08:00.350
The stars light vastly
outshines a planets light.

00:08:00.350 --> 00:08:04.020
Planets are just little specks
compared to giant stars.

00:08:04.020 --> 00:08:07.190
Ten billion times brighter
typically.

00:08:07.190 --> 00:08:09.670
But our technology got
better and better so instead

00:08:09.670 --> 00:08:14.500 position:56%
of seeing our planets we could allow
ourselves to detect them indirectly.

00:08:14.500 --> 00:08:16.690
One method is called the
radial velocity method.

00:08:16.690 --> 00:08:20.760
And what this relies on are
just simple Newtonian mechanics,

00:08:20.760 --> 00:08:22.710
you remember Isaac Newton
put together a picture

00:08:22.710 --> 00:08:26.110
of how the solar system works
and it's based on gravity.

00:08:26.110 --> 00:08:28.880
And we know that all stars
are obeying these laws.

00:08:28.880 --> 00:08:34.140
So if a star has a planet
orbiting it, we know from Newton

00:08:34.140 --> 00:08:36.990
that they're orbiting a
common center of mass.

00:08:36.990 --> 00:08:39.760
It's not the star being
completely static

00:08:39.760 --> 00:08:41.930
and the planets orbiting
around the star.

00:08:41.930 --> 00:08:43.750
They're actually both in orbit.

00:08:43.750 --> 00:08:46.610
The planets orbit is bigger
because the center of mass,

00:08:46.610 --> 00:08:50.170
where most of the mass is,
is inside the star typically

00:08:50.170 --> 00:08:51.470
for a small planet.

00:08:51.470 --> 00:08:54.380
But that doesn't mean the
start doesn't move at all.

00:08:54.380 --> 00:08:58.130
If our technology gets good enough
we can detect that tiny wobble

00:08:58.130 --> 00:09:00.130
from a star that's telling us

00:09:00.130 --> 00:09:03.340
that a planet is imparting
that wobble on it.

00:09:03.340 --> 00:09:05.120
It's called the Radial
Velocity Method.

00:09:05.120 --> 00:09:08.240
And the was really getting
going in the mid 90s.

00:09:08.240 --> 00:09:11.990 position:56%
Of course we were looking for solar
systems that looked a lot like ours.

00:09:11.990 --> 00:09:14.440
We knew big planets were going
to be the ones that imparted

00:09:14.440 --> 00:09:17.240
that signal strongest on the stars.

00:09:17.240 --> 00:09:20.260
But the big planets in our solar
system are Jupiter, Saturn,

00:09:20.260 --> 00:09:23.600
they are way, way far
beyond where the earth is.

00:09:23.600 --> 00:09:28.240
They take years to go around the
sun, 5, 10 maybe even longer years.

00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:31.530
So people were looking for signals
in their data from big planets

00:09:31.530 --> 00:09:35.070
that they thought would be
like Jupiter and Saturn.

00:09:35.070 --> 00:09:38.410
They were so focused on what
they were expecting to see

00:09:38.410 --> 00:09:40.790
from our solar system that
many of the scientists

00:09:40.790 --> 00:09:43.940
who were working this area
missed the first signals.

00:09:43.940 --> 00:09:46.640
This is actually the
discovery image.

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:50.150
It's actually the confirmation
image by a group, Jeff Marcy

00:09:50.150 --> 00:09:55.110
and Paul Butler, who confirmed
a planet call 51 Peg b,

00:09:55.110 --> 00:09:59.080
orbiting the star 51 in
the constellation Pegasus.

00:09:59.080 --> 00:10:03.110
So what you see there is going
up and down is the velocity

00:10:03.110 --> 00:10:06.550
of the star coming towards
us and moving away from us.

00:10:06.550 --> 00:10:11.350
Towards and away, in a perfectly
periodic way that's telling us what

00:10:11.350 --> 00:10:13.920
the orbit of that planet was.

00:10:13.920 --> 00:10:17.790
It was actually on a few
days orbit, less than 5 days.

00:10:17.790 --> 00:10:22.770 position:56%
Much, much closer than any planet in
our solar system and quite massive,

00:10:22.770 --> 00:10:25.820
almost the mass of Jupiter, to
be able to impart that signal.

00:10:25.820 --> 00:10:27.450
This was a watershed event.

00:10:27.450 --> 00:10:30.620
It was like the earth
rise image for scientists

00:10:30.620 --> 00:10:33.380
because we now had evidence
that there were planets

00:10:33.380 --> 00:10:37.620
around other stars and that first
planet was so surprising compared

00:10:37.620 --> 00:10:39.390
to what our solar system
has that we had

00:10:39.390 --> 00:10:42.220
to rethink how we were
looking for exoplanets.

00:10:42.220 --> 00:10:44.540
So it's hard to read
this in the light,

00:10:44.540 --> 00:10:49.060
