00:26:12.690 --> 00:26:16.810
Seven out of ten stars in the
milky way are thought to be M stars

00:26:16.810 --> 00:26:20.570
and the stars closest
to us are small stars.

00:26:20.570 --> 00:26:21.870
So they're important.

00:26:21.870 --> 00:26:23.560
They're becoming increasingly
important as we think

00:26:23.560 --> 00:26:26.430
about finding planets,
because what Kepler told us is

00:26:26.430 --> 00:26:30.000
that planets are everywhere and
we saw that a lot of M stars seem

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:32.340
to have a lot of smaller
planets around them.

00:26:32.340 --> 00:26:35.650
That it's common to make smaller
planets around smaller stars.

00:26:35.650 --> 00:26:37.640
And the other thing that's
really exciting about them is

00:26:37.640 --> 00:26:41.470 position:56%
that the habitable zone is really
crunched in around these small stars

00:26:41.470 --> 00:26:43.710
and that means that that
transit that you're looking for,

00:26:43.710 --> 00:26:45.010
or anything that you're
looking for on

00:26:45.010 --> 00:26:48.350
that periodic signal,
happens much more often.

00:26:48.350 --> 00:26:49.780
Weeks typically.

00:26:49.780 --> 00:26:53.020
So if you want to observe something
over and over again for a planet,

00:26:53.020 --> 00:26:54.730
a small planet around
an M star is going

00:26:54.730 --> 00:26:57.960 position:56%
to give you a lot more opportunities
in a given say, observing season

00:26:57.960 --> 00:27:01.450
at a telescope, than something
like earth around the sun.

00:27:01.450 --> 00:27:05.910
So a lot of our attention is being
turned towards the smaller M stars

00:27:05.910 --> 00:27:08.430
in the galaxy now when we
think about how we're going

00:27:08.430 --> 00:27:10.320
to take the next steps from Kepler

00:27:10.320 --> 00:27:13.860
and find those really
earth like planets.

00:27:13.860 --> 00:27:18.500
But there are some problems and
some challenges with M stars.

00:27:18.500 --> 00:27:21.960
It turns out that M stars
are incredibly active.

00:27:21.960 --> 00:27:25.210
So sometimes you're probably
hearing about solar flares

00:27:25.210 --> 00:27:29.520
that they're predicting are going
to perhaps impact your cable signal

00:27:29.520 --> 00:27:31.260 position:56%
or maybe the GPS for a little while.

00:27:31.260 --> 00:27:33.860
Or maybe you're going to be
able to see an aurora down here

00:27:33.860 --> 00:27:37.020
in southern latitudes
because of the suns activity.

00:27:37.020 --> 00:27:41.860
Remember I told you the sun is
a very calm, low activity star.

00:27:41.860 --> 00:27:44.920
M stars are hundreds
of times more active.

00:27:44.920 --> 00:27:48.250
They give out huge flares
that dwarf solar flares

00:27:48.250 --> 00:27:51.050
and they do it much more typical.

00:27:51.050 --> 00:27:52.670
So much more often.

00:27:52.670 --> 00:27:55.310
This means that any planet that's
really close to that M star

00:27:55.310 --> 00:27:57.610
and going around really
quickly, could be bombarded,

00:27:57.610 --> 00:28:01.770
probably is bombarded with high
energy radiation all the time.

00:28:01.770 --> 00:28:05.050 position:56%
So even if they're in that habitable
zone it could be a trick for it

00:28:05.050 --> 00:28:08.390
to really be something where you
could get habitability happening.

00:28:08.390 --> 00:28:12.480
Also, planets that are
close to stars tend

00:28:12.480 --> 00:28:14.710
to synchronize their
orbit and their spin,

00:28:14.710 --> 00:28:17.570
just like the moon has
synchronized its orbit and spin

00:28:17.570 --> 00:28:18.930
with respect to the earth.

00:28:18.930 --> 00:28:23.570
So we always see the same face
of the moon facing the earth.

00:28:23.570 --> 00:28:27.020
A planet would always see
the same part of the sun.

00:28:27.020 --> 00:28:28.320
I should say it the
other way around.

00:28:28.320 --> 00:28:29.620
If you're on a planet that's in one

00:28:29.620 --> 00:28:33.260
of these M star orbits you're quick
likely to have got tidally locked

00:28:33.260 --> 00:28:34.860
and you could either be
on that side of the planet

00:28:34.860 --> 00:28:37.370
that always faces the
sun or maybe on the side

00:28:37.370 --> 00:28:39.430
that never faces the sun.

00:28:39.430 --> 00:28:42.630
Or maybe lucky enough to
be on that Terminator area.

00:28:42.630 --> 00:28:44.560
Maybe the planet would
wobble a little bit

00:28:44.560 --> 00:28:47.060
and you would get something
like a day/night cycle.

00:28:47.060 --> 00:28:49.910
But typically we expect
these to be tidally locked

00:28:49.910 --> 00:28:54.180
which gives you all kinds
of habitability issues.

00:28:54.180 --> 00:28:57.570
But we're still working hard to
study these phenomena and figure

00:28:57.570 --> 00:29:00.870
out what could really be
going on in these systems

00:29:00.870 --> 00:29:02.170
that are so different from ours.

00:29:02.170 --> 00:29:05.700 position:56%
And the thing that I think is really
exciting about this particular area

00:29:05.700 --> 00:29:09.490
of research is it really
joins together all the areas

00:29:09.490 --> 00:29:10.800
of astrophysics.

00:29:10.800 --> 00:29:15.480
So you have to understand our
sun very well, the flare dynamics

00:29:15.480 --> 00:29:18.600
and time variability, to have
some sense of other stars that are

00:29:18.600 --> 00:29:21.820
like it and to be able to compare
what's happening on other stars

00:29:21.820 --> 00:29:24.740
as far as their flares go with
what we know so well about the sun.

00:29:24.740 --> 00:29:26.050
The sun is very well studied.

00:29:26.050 --> 00:29:28.500 position:56%
We have reams of data about the sun.

00:29:28.500 --> 00:29:31.530
Also, we're learning about
what happens to these planets

00:29:31.530 --> 00:29:35.440
around other stars by studying
the planets in our own system.

00:29:35.440 --> 00:29:39.720
Getting better refinements of
how our own solar system formed.

